# Accessibility Domain
# Source: synthesized from WCAG 2.2, ARIA Authoring Practices Guide, and production repositories
version: 1

patterns:
  - id: semantic-html-first
    title: Semantic HTML over ARIA
    description: >
      Use native HTML elements before reaching for ARIA. Buttons, links, headings,
      lists, and form controls carry implicit roles and behaviors that browsers and
      assistive technologies understand natively. ARIA is a fallback for when no
      native element fits, not a first choice.
    example: |
      <!-- Good: native button carries role, keyboard, and focus behavior -->
      <button type="button" onclick="openMenu()">Open Menu</button>

      <!-- Bad: custom element needs ARIA role + tabindex + keyboard handler -->
      <div role="button" tabindex="0" onclick="openMenu()" onkeydown="...">Open Menu</div>

  - id: focus-management-spa
    title: Focus management in SPAs
    description: >
      When a route change or panel open/close occurs, move focus programmatically so
      screen reader users are not stranded at the old location. For modals, trap focus
      inside the dialog while it is open. Restore focus to the trigger element when the
      modal closes.
    example: |
      // On route change -- move focus to the new page heading
      useEffect(() => {
        document.getElementById('page-heading')?.focus();
      }, [location.pathname]);

      // On modal close -- restore focus to the element that opened it
      function closeModal() {
        setOpen(false);
        triggerRef.current?.focus();
      }

  - id: keyboard-nav-visual-order
    title: Keyboard navigation matches visual order
    description: >
      The DOM order of focusable elements should match the visual reading order.
      Users navigating by Tab expect to move left-to-right, top-to-bottom in the
      same sequence they see on screen. CSS layout (grid, flexbox, position) can
      visually reorder elements while the DOM order stays incorrect.
    example: |
      <!-- DOM order matches visual left-to-right, top-to-bottom layout -->
      <nav>...</nav>
      <main>
        <h1>Page Title</h1>
        <article>...</article>
        <aside>...</aside>
      </main>
      <footer>...</footer>

  - id: color-contrast-ratios
    title: Minimum color contrast ratios (WCAG 2.2 AA)
    description: >
      Normal text (below 18pt or 14pt bold) requires a contrast ratio of at least
      4.5:1 against its background. Large text (18pt or 14pt bold and above) requires
      3:1. UI components and graphical objects require 3:1 against adjacent colors.
      Use a contrast checker during design, not as an afterthought.
    example: |
      /* Good: #1a1a1a on #ffffff = 19.1:1 ratio */
      body { color: #1a1a1a; background: #ffffff; }

      /* Bad: #767676 on #ffffff = 4.48:1 -- fails by a hair for normal text */
      .muted { color: #767676; background: #ffffff; }

  - id: touch-target-size
    title: Touch target minimum 44x44px
    description: >
      Interactive elements on touch devices must have a minimum tap target of 44x44 CSS
      pixels per WCAG 2.2 SC 2.5.8. Use padding to enlarge small icons without changing
      their visual size. Spacing between adjacent targets can substitute for larger
      individual targets (WCAG 2.2 allows 24x24 with at least 24px offset).
    example: |
      /* Icon button: visually 24px, touch target 44px via padding */
      .icon-btn {
        display: inline-flex;
        align-items: center;
        justify-content: center;
        width: 24px;
        height: 24px;
        padding: 10px;        /* 24 + 20 = 44px tap area */
        box-sizing: content-box;
      }

  - id: alt-text-strategy
    title: Alt text strategy for images
    description: >
      Decorative images get alt="" so screen readers skip them. Informative images get
      a concise description of their content. Functional images (icons inside buttons)
      get alt text that describes the action, not the image itself. Never use file names
      or "image of" as alt text.
    example: |
      <!-- Decorative: skip it -->
      <img src="divider.svg" alt="" role="presentation">

      <!-- Informative: describe content -->
      <img src="chart.png" alt="Bar chart showing Q1 sales up 12% year over year">

      <!-- Functional: describe action -->
      <button><img src="search-icon.svg" alt="Search"></button>

  - id: form-labeling
    title: Explicit form labeling
    description: >
      Every form control needs a programmatically associated label. Prefer explicit
      <label for="id"> pairing. Use aria-label when a visible label would be redundant
      (search input next to a Search button). Use aria-labelledby to point to existing
      visible text. Never rely on placeholder text as the sole label.
    example: |
      <!-- Explicit label: preferred -->
      <label for="email">Email address</label>
      <input type="email" id="email" name="email">

      <!-- aria-label: acceptable when no visible text needed -->
      <input type="search" aria-label="Search products" placeholder="Search...">

      <!-- aria-labelledby: reuse existing heading text -->
      <h2 id="billing-heading">Billing address</h2>
      <input type="text" aria-labelledby="billing-heading" name="billing-street">

  - id: skip-navigation
    title: Skip navigation links
    description: >
      Provide a "Skip to main content" link as the first focusable element on the page.
      This allows keyboard and screen reader users to bypass repeated navigation blocks.
      The link can be visually hidden until focused. It must be focusable and must point
      to the main landmark or heading.
    example: |
      <a class="skip-link" href="#main-content">Skip to main content</a>
      <nav>...</nav>
      <main id="main-content" tabindex="-1">...</main>

      /* CSS: visually hidden until focused */
      .skip-link { position: absolute; top: -40px; }
      .skip-link:focus { top: 0; }

  - id: live-regions
    title: Live regions for dynamic content
    description: >
      Use aria-live to announce dynamic changes to screen readers without moving focus.
      aria-live="polite" waits for the user to be idle -- use for status messages,
      search results, and form feedback. aria-live="assertive" interrupts immediately --
      use only for critical errors or time-sensitive alerts. Keep live region content
      concise and inject only the changed text.
    example: |
      <!-- Polite: status message after form submit -->
      <div aria-live="polite" aria-atomic="true" class="sr-only" id="status"></div>

      <!-- Assertive: critical error -->
      <div role="alert" aria-live="assertive" id="error-announce"></div>

      // Inject message after action
      document.getElementById('status').textContent = 'Form submitted successfully.';

anti_patterns:
  - id: color-only-information
    title: Using color alone to convey information
    description: >
      Do not rely solely on color to distinguish states, errors, or categories. Users
      with color vision deficiency (about 8% of males) will miss the information.
      Always pair color with a secondary indicator: icon, pattern, label, or shape.
      WCAG SC 1.4.1 prohibits color as the sole visual means of conveying information.

  - id: placeholder-as-label
    title: Placeholder text as label replacement
    description: >
      Placeholder text disappears when the user starts typing, leaving them with no
      reminder of what the field requires. Screen readers do not consistently expose
      placeholder as an accessible name. Always use a real <label> element. Placeholder
      is acceptable as supplemental hint text only when a visible label is already present.

  - id: positive-tabindex
    title: tabindex > 0
    description: >
      Setting tabindex="1" or any positive integer removes an element from the natural
      DOM tab order and creates a parallel focus sequence that breaks keyboard navigation.
      Positive tabindex values cause the element to receive focus before all tabindex="0"
      elements regardless of position. Use tabindex="0" to add an element to natural order
      or tabindex="-1" to make it programmatically focusable only.

  - id: display-none-for-sr-content
    title: Hiding content with display:none that should be screen-reader-visible
    description: >
      display:none and visibility:hidden both remove content from the accessibility tree.
      Use them only when content should be hidden from everyone. To visually hide content
      while keeping it available to screen readers, use the sr-only CSS pattern (clip, not
      display:none). To hide content from screen readers but show it visually, use
      aria-hidden="true".

  - id: aria-role-override
    title: ARIA roles that override correct implicit HTML semantics
    description: >
      Assigning role="presentation" or role="none" to a semantic element strips its
      meaning from the accessibility tree. Adding role="button" to an <a> element
      changes how assistive technology announces it without preserving link behavior.
      Adding ARIA landmark roles to <div> when a native landmark element (<nav>, <main>,
      <aside>) exists adds noise. Use ARIA roles only when no native element matches.

gotchas:
  - id: nvda-chrome-vs-jaws-ie
    title: NVDA+Chrome vs JAWS behavior differences
    description: >
      NVDA with Chrome and JAWS with older IE/Edge do not expose ARIA identically.
      JAWS reads aria-label on container elements differently than NVDA does. Dynamic
      content injected into live regions fires inconsistently across combinations.
      Testing with a single screen reader is insufficient for a production release.
    fix: >
      Test the critical happy path with at least two screen reader combinations:
      NVDA+Chrome and JAWS+Chrome (or JAWS+Edge). Document which combination was used
      in QA notes. Reference the a11y support matrix at https://a11ysupport.io before
      using any ARIA feature.

  - id: voiceover-ios-vs-macos
    title: VoiceOver on iOS vs macOS differences
    description: >
      VoiceOver on iOS uses swipe gestures for navigation and does not expose all ARIA
      patterns the same way the macOS VoiceOver does. Custom component interactions that
      work on desktop may be completely broken on iOS because touch events and keyboard
      events are handled differently.
    fix: >
      Test interactive components (carousels, custom dropdowns, date pickers) on an
      actual iOS device with VoiceOver, not just macOS. Key differences: swipe navigation
      skips elements that only handle keydown events; focus trapping in modals requires
      specific iOS VoiceOver patterns.

  - id: dynamic-content-not-announced
    title: Dynamic content that does not announce to screen readers
    description: >
      Injecting new content into the DOM after a user action (search results, filtered
      lists, toast notifications) will be silently ignored by screen readers unless the
      injection target has an aria-live attribute or focus is moved to the new content.
    fix: >
      For search results and filtered content: either move focus to the result count
      heading or use an aria-live="polite" region that announces the count. For
      toast/notification messages: use role="status" or role="alert" depending on urgency.

  - id: modal-focus-trap
    title: Modal dialogs that do not trap focus
    description: >
      Without a focus trap, Tab key navigation leaves the modal and cycles through the
      obscured background content. Screen reader users can also navigate out of the dialog
      using virtual cursor mode. This breaks the modal contract and allows interaction
      with inert background elements.
    fix: >
      Implement focus trapping: on modal open, intercept Tab and Shift+Tab to cycle focus
      within the dialog. Apply inert attribute (or aria-hidden="true") to the background
      content container. On close, remove inert and restore focus to the trigger. Use a
      tested library (focus-trap-react, Headless UI) rather than a custom implementation.

  - id: custom-dropdown-keyboard
    title: Custom dropdowns that break keyboard navigation
    description: >
      Custom select/combobox components often handle click events but miss full keyboard
      support: arrow keys to navigate options, Enter/Space to select, Escape to close,
      Home/End to jump to first/last, and type-ahead character search. The ARIA Combobox
      pattern specifies all required keyboard interactions.
    fix: >
      Follow the ARIA Authoring Practices Guide combobox pattern exactly. Prefer native
      <select> for simple single-value selection. Use a battle-tested headless component
      (Radix UI, Headless UI, Downshift) for complex combo boxes.

  - id: missing-aria-required-attributes
    title: ARIA required attributes missing
    description: >
      Many ARIA roles require companion attributes to be valid and useful. role="button"
      on a toggle needs aria-pressed. A disclosure widget needs aria-expanded. An element
      that controls another panel needs aria-controls pointing to the controlled element's
      id. Missing required attributes cause validators to flag errors and screen readers
      to announce incomplete state.
    fix: >
      Before shipping any custom interactive component, run axe-core or Lighthouse
      accessibility audit. Check the ARIA spec for the role's required states and
      properties. Add aria-expanded, aria-controls, aria-pressed, aria-selected, or
      aria-checked as the role demands. Keep these attributes updated in sync with
      visual state via JavaScript.


