### devops

# DevOps and CI/CD Patterns
# Source: synthesized from production repositories and best practices
version: 1

patterns:
  - id: reusable-workflows
    title: GitHub Actions reusable workflows for shared CI logic
    description: >
      Extract common CI steps (lint, test, build, deploy) into reusable workflows
      (workflow_call trigger). Callers pass inputs and secrets. This eliminates
      copy-paste drift across repos and allows a single change to the reusable
      workflow to propagate everywhere. Reusable workflows can be versioned by
      ref (SHA or tag).
    example: |
      # .github/workflows/reusable-node-ci.yml (in shared repo)
      on:
        workflow_call:
          inputs:
            node-version:
              type: string
              default: "20"
          secrets:
            NPM_TOKEN:
              required: true
      jobs:
        ci:
          runs-on: ubuntu-latest
          steps:
            - uses: actions/checkout@a5ac7e51b41094c92402da3b24376905139b7f7d  # v4.1.6
            - uses: actions/setup-node@60edb5dd545a775178f52524783378180af0d1f8  # v4.0.2
              with:
                node-version: ${{ inputs.node-version }}
                cache: npm
            - run: npm ci
            - run: npm test

      # Caller workflow
      # jobs:
      #   ci:
      #     uses: my-org/shared-workflows/.github/workflows/reusable-node-ci.yml@main
      #     secrets: inherit

  - id: oidc-cloud-auth
    title: OIDC federation for cloud authentication (no long-lived secrets)
    description: >
      GitHub Actions can authenticate to AWS, GCP, and Azure via OIDC without
      storing static credentials as secrets. The workflow requests a short-lived
      token from the GitHub OIDC provider, which the cloud provider trusts via
      a configured trust relationship. Tokens expire with the workflow run.
    example: |
      # AWS OIDC -- requires IAM role with GitHub OIDC trust policy
      jobs:
        deploy:
          runs-on: ubuntu-latest
          permissions:
            id-token: write   # required for OIDC
            contents: read
          steps:
            - uses: actions/checkout@a5ac7e51b41094c92402da3b24376905139b7f7d
            - uses: aws-actions/configure-aws-credentials@e3dd6a429d7300a6a4c196c26e071d42e0343502  # v4.0.2
              with:
                role-to-assume: arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/github-actions-deploy
                aws-region: us-east-1
            - run: aws s3 cp dist/ s3://my-bucket/ --recursive

  - id: sha-pinned-actions
    title: Pin third-party actions to full commit SHA
    description: >
      Action tags (v4) and branches (main) are mutable -- a tag can be moved to point
      to a different commit. Pinning to a full SHA (immutable) prevents supply chain
      attacks where a compromised action repo pushes malicious code under an existing
      tag. Use Dependabot to keep SHA pins up-to-date automatically.
    example: |
      # dependabot.yml -- auto-updates action SHA pins
      version: 2
      updates:
        - package-ecosystem: "github-actions"
          directory: "/"
          schedule:
            interval: "weekly"
          groups:
            actions:
              patterns:
                - "actions/*"

      # In workflow: pin to SHA, comment with version for readability
      - uses: actions/checkout@a5ac7e51b41094c92402da3b24376905139b7f7d  # v4.1.6

  - id: artifact-caching
    title: Cache dependencies to reduce CI wall time
    description: >
      The actions/cache action stores and restores dependency directories keyed
      by a hash of the lockfile. Cache hits skip reinstalling hundreds of packages.
      Always include the lockfile hash in the cache key so a changed lockfile
      busts the cache and triggers a fresh install.
    example: |
      - uses: actions/cache@0c45773b623bea8c8e75f6c82b208c3cf94ea4f9  # v4.0.2
        with:
          path: |
            ~/.npm
            node_modules
          key: ${{ runner.os }}-node-${{ hashFiles('**/package-lock.json') }}
          restore-keys: |
            ${{ runner.os }}-node-

  - id: matrix-builds
    title: Matrix strategy for multi-version and multi-platform testing
    description: >
      Matrix builds test combinations of OS, language version, or configuration
      in parallel with minimal YAML repetition. Use 'fail-fast: false' so one
      failing combination does not cancel the others (valuable for understanding
      cross-platform differences).
    example: |
      jobs:
        test:
          runs-on: ${{ matrix.os }}
          strategy:
            fail-fast: false
            matrix:
              os: [ubuntu-latest, windows-latest, macos-latest]
              node: ["18", "20", "22"]
          steps:
            - uses: actions/checkout@a5ac7e51b41094c92402da3b24376905139b7f7d
            - uses: actions/setup-node@60edb5dd545a775178f52524783378180af0d1f8
              with:
                node-version: ${{ matrix.node }}
            - run: npm ci && npm test

  - id: environment-protection-rules
    title: Environment protection rules as deployment gates
    description: >
      GitHub Environments (Settings -> Environments) support required reviewers,
      wait timers, and branch restrictions. Production deploys require a human
      approval before the workflow can proceed. The environment name in the workflow
      job triggers the protection rules.
    example: |
      jobs:
        deploy-prod:
          runs-on: ubuntu-latest
          environment:
            name: production
            url: https://app.example.com
          steps:
            - run: ./scripts/deploy.sh

  - id: branch-protection-required-checks
    title: Branch protection with required status checks
    description: >
      Protect main/master with: require PR before merge, require status checks
      to pass (CI, linting), require up-to-date branches, restrict who can push.
      Use 'Require deployments to succeed' for environment-gated merges.
      Configure via gh CLI or terraform (github_branch_protection resource).
    example: |
      # Configure via gh CLI
      gh api repos/{owner}/{repo}/branches/main/protection \
        --method PUT \
        --field required_status_checks='{"strict":true,"contexts":["ci/test","ci/lint"]}' \
        --field enforce_admins=true \
        --field required_pull_request_reviews='{"required_approving_review_count":1}' \
        --field restrictions=null

  - id: docker-layer-caching
    title: Docker BuildKit cache mounts for faster image builds
    description: >
      BuildKit RUN --mount=type=cache caches package manager directories between
      builds. Combined with multi-stage builds, this keeps final image sizes small
      while dramatically speeding up CI builds that change only application code,
      not dependencies.
    example: |
      # Dockerfile with BuildKit cache mounts
      FROM node:20-alpine AS builder
      WORKDIR /app
      COPY package*.json ./
      RUN --mount=type=cache,target=/root/.npm \
          npm ci --only=production
      COPY . .
      RUN npm run build

      FROM node:20-alpine AS runtime
      WORKDIR /app
      COPY --from=builder /app/dist ./dist
      COPY --from=builder /app/node_modules ./node_modules
      USER node
      CMD ["node", "dist/index.js"]

anti_patterns:
  - id: long-lived-cloud-credentials
    title: Storing cloud credentials as long-lived GitHub secrets
    description: >
      Static AWS access keys stored as GitHub secrets never expire. If leaked via
      a log, artifact, or compromised workflow, they grant persistent access until
      manually rotated. Use OIDC federation -- credentials exist only for the
      duration of the workflow run.

  - id: mutable-action-refs
    title: Pinning actions to a branch or mutable tag
    description: >
      uses: actions/checkout@main or uses: actions/checkout@v4 resolves to whatever
      commit those refs point to at run time. A supply chain attack on the action
      repo can inject malicious code that runs in your CI with your secrets.
      Always pin to a full commit SHA.

  - id: secrets-in-run-commands
    title: Echoing or printing secrets in run steps
    description: >
      GitHub masks known secrets in logs, but 'echo $SECRET | base64' or variations
      can bypass masking. Secrets in run steps also appear in verbose tool output.
      Pass secrets via environment variables, not inline command arguments.
      Never run 'env' or 'printenv' in CI steps.

  - id: no-permissions-declaration
    title: Omitting permissions block, relying on default GITHUB_TOKEN scope
    description: >
      Default GITHUB_TOKEN permissions vary by repo setting (read-all or write-all).
      Workflows without an explicit permissions block may get more access than needed
      (write to contents, packages, deployments). Always declare the minimal set
      per-workflow and per-job.

  - id: no-timeout-minutes
    title: Jobs without timeout-minutes run indefinitely on hung processes
    description: >
      A hung test suite, infinite loop, or waiting for a resource that never appears
      will consume a GitHub-hosted runner for the maximum billing window (6 hours by
      default). Always set timeout-minutes at the job level. Standard CI jobs should
      complete in under 20 minutes.

gotchas:
  - id: github-token-scope-limits
    title: GITHUB_TOKEN cannot trigger downstream workflows
    description: >
      A workflow triggered by GITHUB_TOKEN push events does NOT trigger further
      workflow runs on those commits. This prevents infinite loops but also means
      push-to-release workflows that create a commit will not trigger CI on that
      commit. Use a PAT or GitHub App token when the commit must trigger CI.
    fix: >
      Use a GitHub App installation token or a PAT stored as a secret when a
      workflow commit needs to trigger another workflow.

  - id: fork-pr-secrets-blocked
    title: Secrets not available in fork pull request workflows
    description: >
      Workflows triggered by pull_request from a fork run with a read-only
      GITHUB_TOKEN and NO access to repository secrets. This is intentional
      security behavior. The fork author cannot access secrets even if the workflow
      references them -- the values are empty strings. Use pull_request_target
      carefully (it runs with write perms and secrets but in the context of the base
      branch, not the fork -- dangerous for untrusted code).
    fix: >
      For fork PRs: keep CI jobs secret-free (test without deploy). Gate deployment
      jobs on a label added by a maintainer or use Environments with required
      reviewers before any secret-consuming step.

  - id: concurrent-workflow-conflicts
    title: Concurrent workflow runs can race on shared resources
    description: >
      Two PRs merged simultaneously can trigger two concurrent deploy workflows.
      Both try to push to the same S3 bucket or deploy to the same environment,
      causing partial deploys or state corruption. Use concurrency groups to
      serialize workflow runs on shared resources.
    fix: >
      Add to workflow (cancels in-progress run on same ref):
      concurrency:
        group: deploy-${{ github.ref }}
        cancel-in-progress: true
      For environments, use cancel-in-progress: false to queue instead of cancel.

  - id: cache-poisoning-risk
    title: Untrusted PRs can poison shared caches
    description: >
      If cache keys are not scoped per-branch, a malicious PR can write a cache
      entry that gets restored by a subsequent trusted workflow run. The cache
      contains node_modules or build artifacts that execute during CI. Scope cache
      keys to include the branch or use read-only cache access for fork PRs.
    fix: >
      Use restore-keys with a base key for reads but write only on the main branch.
      Never restore an untrusted PR's cache entry in a privileged workflow.

  - id: artifact-size-limits
    title: GitHub Actions artifacts have size limits and short retention
    description: >
      Default artifact retention is 90 days (configurable down to 1 day). Per-run
      artifact size limit is 500MB for public repos and 2GB for private. Uploading
      large build outputs or node_modules as artifacts hits these limits silently --
      the upload step succeeds but download fails. Use actions/upload-artifact v4
      which fails loudly on size violations.
    fix: >
      Compress artifacts before upload. For large binaries, push to S3 or a container
      registry instead. Set retention-days explicitly to match your policy.


### documentation

# Documentation Domain
# Source: synthesized from Diataxis framework, Keep a Changelog, and production documentation practices
version: 1

patterns:
  - id: diataxis-quadrants
    title: Diataxis quadrants -- right type for the right goal
    description: >
      Documentation falls into four distinct quadrants with different reader goals.
      Tutorial: learning-oriented, guides a beginner through a practical exercise to build
      competence. How-to guide: task-oriented, solves a specific problem for a practitioner
      who already has context. Reference: information-oriented, describes the system
      accurately and completely. Explanation: understanding-oriented, discusses concepts,
      context, and decisions. Mixing quadrants in a single page degrades all of them.
    example: |
      Tutorial:  "Build your first API integration" (step-by-step, holds hand)
      How-to:    "How to authenticate with OAuth 2.0" (goal-focused, no hand-holding)
      Reference: "API endpoints -- /users" (complete, dry, no narrative)
      Explanation: "Why we chose event sourcing over CRUD" (concepts, trade-offs)

  - id: progressive-disclosure
    title: Progressive disclosure -- overview then details
    description: >
      Start every page with the minimum information needed to understand what it covers
      and whether it is the right page. Add detail in layers. A reader skimming to orient
      should get value from the first paragraph alone. A reader who needs implementation
      details finds them by reading further.
    example: |
      ## Caching
      The cache stores API responses to reduce latency and cost. It uses an LRU eviction
      policy with a configurable TTL.

      ### How the cache works
      [deeper explanation here]

      ### Configuration reference
      [full option table here]

  - id: task-oriented-titles
    title: Task-oriented titles for procedural docs
    description: >
      How-to guides and tutorials should have titles phrased as actions or outcomes, not
      nouns. "How to configure rate limiting" is findable by someone who has a problem.
      "Rate Limiting Configuration" is findable only by someone who already knows the term.
      Sentence case for headings. No trailing periods.
    example: |
      Good titles:
        "How to set up authentication"
        "Deploy to production"
        "Migrate from v1 to v2"

      Bad titles:
        "Authentication Setup"
        "Production Deployment"
        "Migration Guide" (vague -- from what to what?)

  - id: clean-code-examples
    title: Code examples that copy-paste clean
    description: >
      Every code example must be syntactically valid and runnable as shown. Include all
      required imports and setup steps if they are not already in a preceding code block
      on the same page. Use realistic but minimal values (no enterprise-length config
      files). Test code examples as part of CI -- broken examples are worse than no examples.
    example: |
      ```python
      # Complete, runnable example -- no hidden setup required
      import httpx

      client = httpx.Client(base_url="https://api.example.com")
      response = client.get("/users", headers={"Authorization": "Bearer YOUR_TOKEN"})
      print(response.json())
      ```

  - id: version-docs-with-code
    title: Versioning docs with code
    description: >
      Documentation must be version-pinned to the code it describes. Storing docs in
      the same repository as the code (docs-as-code) is the most reliable way to keep
      them in sync. Tag doc releases with the same version tag as code releases. Use
      a versioned docs system (Docusaurus versions, ReadTheDocs versions) when multiple
      major versions are actively supported.
    example: |
      # Repository structure: docs live beside the code they describe
      /
        src/
        docs/
          api-reference.md
          changelog.md
        CHANGELOG.md   # top-level, always current
        package.json   # version here = version docs describe

  - id: api-reference-auto-generation
    title: API reference auto-generated from code
    description: >
      Hand-maintained API reference diverges from the actual code within weeks.
      Generate reference docs from source -- JSDoc/TSDoc for TypeScript/JavaScript,
      docstrings + Sphinx for Python, OpenAPI annotations for REST APIs. Keep the
      generator in CI so docs fail the build if the code and docs desync.
    example: |
      # TypeScript: TSDoc comment drives the reference page
      /**
       * Authenticates a user and returns a session token.
       * @param email - The user's email address
       * @param password - The user's password (min 8 characters)
       * @returns A JWT session token valid for 24 hours
       * @throws {AuthError} When credentials are invalid
       */
      async function login(email: string, password: string): Promise<string>

  - id: keep-a-changelog
    title: Changelog format -- Keep a Changelog
    description: >
      Use the Keep a Changelog format: each release has a date and version, changes
      are grouped under Added / Changed / Deprecated / Removed / Fixed / Security.
      The top entry is always [Unreleased]. Semantic versioning drives the version
      numbers. Changelogs are written for humans, not generated from commit messages.
    example: |
      ## [Unreleased]

      ## [2.1.0] - 2026-04-15
      ### Added
      - OAuth 2.0 support for all authentication endpoints

      ### Fixed
      - Rate limit counter no longer resets on partial window overlap

      ## [2.0.1] - 2026-03-01
      ### Security
      - Patched CSRF vulnerability in session cookie handling

  - id: readme-structure
    title: README structure -- what/why/quickstart/link
    description: >
      A README answers four questions in order: what is this, why would I use it,
      how do I get started in 60 seconds, where is the full documentation. Keep the
      quickstart under 10 steps. Never bury the install command below a wall of badges
      or marketing text.
    example: |
      # ProjectName
      One sentence: what it is and what problem it solves.

      ## Why
      Two to three sentences on the problem and why this approach.

      ## Quickstart
      ```bash
      npm install projectname
      ```
      Five lines max to get to Hello World.

      ## Documentation
      Full docs at https://docs.example.com

anti_patterns:
  - id: mixing-tutorial-and-reference
    title: Mixing tutorial and reference in the same page
    description: >
      Tutorial narrative and dry reference tables serve incompatible reader goals. A
      learner following a tutorial does not want to be derailed by an exhaustive option
      table. A practitioner looking up a parameter does not want to read beginner
      motivation text. Keep them in separate files. Link between them.

  - id: assuming-reader-context
    title: Assuming reader context -- missing prerequisites
    description: >
      Docs that start mid-process without stating prerequisites leave readers stuck at
      step 1. State the required environment, installed tools, knowledge level, and any
      prior setup steps at the top of the page. Link to setup guides rather than
      abbreviating them.

  - id: outdated-code-examples
    title: Outdated code examples
    description: >
      Code examples that reference deprecated APIs, removed parameters, or old syntax
      actively mislead readers and damage trust in all documentation. An outdated
      example is worse than no example because it consumes the reader's time debugging
      code that cannot work. Run examples in CI or remove them.

  - id: what-not-why
    title: Documentation that describes what, not why
    description: >
      "This function returns a list of users" describes what already visible in the
      function signature. Documentation earns its keep by explaining why: why this
      design, when to use this vs that, what problem this solves, what the edge cases
      are. Reference docs can describe what. Explanation docs must explain why.

  - id: wall-of-text
    title: Wall of text without scannable headers
    description: >
      Readers do not read documentation linearly -- they scan to find the relevant
      section. Long paragraphs without subheadings force linear reading. Use H2 and
      H3 headings generously. Keep paragraphs under 5 sentences. Use lists and tables
      where comparison or enumeration is needed.

gotchas:
  - id: docs-pass-ci-but-dont-run
    title: Docs that pass CI but do not actually run
    description: >
      Markdown code blocks do not execute in most CI pipelines. A lint pass confirms
      valid markdown syntax but not that the example code runs or produces the correct
      output. Examples can silently break when the underlying API changes.
    fix: >
      Use a doc-testing tool that extracts and runs code examples: doctest for Python,
      mdBook for Rust, custom extraction scripts. At minimum, have a separate CI job
      that installs the library and runs the quickstart example end-to-end on every
      release branch.

  - id: screenshot-drift
    title: Screenshot drift -- UI changes, screenshot stays
    description: >
      Screenshots become stale after every UI change. A screenshot showing a button
      in the wrong place or a dialog with old text destroys reader trust. Screenshots
      are high maintenance and not translatable.
    fix: >
      Minimize screenshot use. Prefer code examples and text descriptions. When
      screenshots are required (setup wizards, GUI-only tools), add them to a
      screenshot refresh checklist that runs before each release. Consider automated
      screenshot capture tools (Percy, Playwright screenshots) tied to release CI.

  - id: i18n-docs-too-late
    title: Internationalization of docs forgotten until too late
    description: >
      When docs are written without i18n in mind, headings use idioms, code examples
      use locale-specific values, and anchor links contain non-ASCII characters. Retrofitting
      i18n after hundreds of pages is extremely expensive.
    fix: >
      Decide on an i18n strategy before writing significant docs: will they be translated,
      and if so by what toolchain (Crowdin, Weblate). Avoid idioms and culture-specific
      examples even if no translation is planned today. Keep anchor IDs as lowercase
      ASCII slugs from day one.

  - id: anchor-link-rot
    title: Anchor link rot from heading changes
    description: >
      Most doc tools auto-generate anchor IDs from heading text. Renaming a heading
      breaks every inbound link to that anchor -- from other docs pages, from external
      sites, and from support tickets. This is silent: no 404 is thrown for in-page
      anchors.
    fix: >
      Use explicit anchor IDs in tools that support them (remark-slug, Docusaurus id
      frontmatter). Run a broken link checker (lychee, markdown-link-check) in CI.
      When renaming a heading, add a redirect or alias for the old anchor if the tool
      supports it.

  - id: search-missing-versioned-docs
    title: Search indexing missing for versioned docs
    description: >
      When a docs site has versioned sections, search indexes often default to only
      the latest version. Users on older versions find no results or find results from
      the wrong version. This causes silent support failures.
    fix: >
      Configure the search tool (Algolia DocSearch, Pagefind) to index all supported
      versions and surface the version label in results. Add a "you are viewing version
      X" banner with a link to the latest. Test search results explicitly for each
      major version during the release process.


