### kubernetes

# Kubernetes Production Patterns
# Source: synthesized from production repositories and best practices
version: 1

patterns:
  - id: resource-requests-limits
    title: Always set resource requests and limits
    description: >
      Every container must declare CPU/memory requests (scheduler uses these to place
      pods) and limits (enforced at runtime). Missing requests cause unpredictable
      scheduling; missing limits cause noisy-neighbor OOMKill cascades.
    example: |
      resources:
        requests:
          cpu: "250m"
          memory: "256Mi"
        limits:
          cpu: "500m"
          memory: "512Mi"

  - id: liveness-vs-readiness-vs-startup
    title: Use the correct probe type for each purpose
    description: >
      Liveness probes restart a container when it deadlocks. Readiness probes remove
      a pod from Service endpoints when it cannot handle traffic. Startup probes give
      slow-starting containers time before liveness kicks in (k8s 1.20+). Using
      liveness where readiness is needed causes thundering-herd restarts.
    example: |
      startupProbe:
        httpGet:
          path: /healthz
          port: 8080
        failureThreshold: 30
        periodSeconds: 10
      readinessProbe:
        httpGet:
          path: /ready
          port: 8080
        initialDelaySeconds: 5
        periodSeconds: 5
      livenessProbe:
        httpGet:
          path: /healthz
          port: 8080
        initialDelaySeconds: 15
        periodSeconds: 20

  - id: rbac-least-privilege
    title: RBAC with least-privilege service accounts
    description: >
      Create a dedicated ServiceAccount per workload. Bind only the verbs and
      resources the workload actually needs. Never mount the default service account
      token in pods that do not need API access. Use automountServiceAccountToken: false
      on the ServiceAccount to opt out by default.
    example: |
      apiVersion: v1
      kind: ServiceAccount
      metadata:
        name: api-server
        namespace: production
      automountServiceAccountToken: false
      ---
      apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
      kind: Role
      metadata:
        name: api-server-role
        namespace: production
      rules:
      - apiGroups: [""]
        resources: ["configmaps"]
        verbs: ["get", "list"]
      ---
      apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
      kind: RoleBinding
      metadata:
        name: api-server-binding
        namespace: production
      subjects:
      - kind: ServiceAccount
        name: api-server
      roleRef:
        kind: Role
        name: api-server-role
        apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io

  - id: network-policy-default-deny
    title: Default-deny NetworkPolicy with explicit allow rules
    description: >
      Apply a default-deny ingress and egress policy to every namespace, then
      explicitly allow only required traffic. This is defense-in-depth -- a
      compromised pod cannot reach arbitrary cluster services without an explicit
      NetworkPolicy allowing it.
    example: |
      # Default deny all ingress and egress
      apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
      kind: NetworkPolicy
      metadata:
        name: default-deny-all
        namespace: production
      spec:
        podSelector: {}
        policyTypes:
        - Ingress
        - Egress
      ---
      # Allow api-server to reach postgres on 5432
      apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
      kind: NetworkPolicy
      metadata:
        name: allow-api-to-postgres
        namespace: production
      spec:
        podSelector:
          matchLabels:
            app: postgres
        ingress:
        - from:
          - podSelector:
              matchLabels:
                app: api-server
          ports:
          - port: 5432

  - id: pod-disruption-budget
    title: PodDisruptionBudget for every stateful or critical workload
    description: >
      PDBs prevent cluster operations (node drain, upgrades) from removing too
      many replicas simultaneously. Without a PDB, a rolling node upgrade can
      take down all replicas of a Deployment at once if they happen to share a node.
    example: |
      apiVersion: policy/v1
      kind: PodDisruptionBudget
      metadata:
        name: api-server-pdb
        namespace: production
      spec:
        minAvailable: 2
        selector:
          matchLabels:
            app: api-server

  - id: hpa-cpu-memory
    title: HorizontalPodAutoscaler with both CPU and memory metrics
    description: >
      HPA v2 (k8s 1.23+) supports multiple metrics. Set CPU and memory targets
      to prevent thrashing. Always set minReplicas >= 2 for availability. Set
      stabilizationWindowSeconds to avoid rapid scale-down after traffic spikes.
    example: |
      apiVersion: autoscaling/v2
      kind: HorizontalPodAutoscaler
      metadata:
        name: api-server-hpa
        namespace: production
      spec:
        scaleTargetRef:
          apiVersion: apps/v1
          kind: Deployment
          name: api-server
        minReplicas: 2
        maxReplicas: 20
        metrics:
        - type: Resource
          resource:
            name: cpu
            target:
              type: Utilization
              averageUtilization: 70
        - type: Resource
          resource:
            name: memory
            target:
              type: Utilization
              averageUtilization: 80
        behavior:
          scaleDown:
            stabilizationWindowSeconds: 300

  - id: rolling-update-strategy
    title: Configure rolling update strategy explicitly
    description: >
      Default maxSurge=25% and maxUnavailable=25% may not suit production. For
      zero-downtime deployments set maxUnavailable: 0 and maxSurge: 1. Always
      combine with readiness probes so new pods receive traffic only when ready.
    example: |
      spec:
        strategy:
          type: RollingUpdate
          rollingUpdate:
            maxSurge: 1
            maxUnavailable: 0
        template:
          spec:
            containers:
            - name: api-server
              readinessProbe:
                httpGet:
                  path: /ready
                  port: 8080
                initialDelaySeconds: 5
                periodSeconds: 3

  - id: secrets-from-external-store
    title: Mount secrets from external store, not k8s Secrets
    description: >
      Kubernetes Secrets are base64-encoded, not encrypted at rest by default (unless
      etcd encryption is configured). Use External Secrets Operator (ESO) to sync from
      AWS Secrets Manager, HashiCorp Vault, or GCP Secret Manager. The Secret object
      in k8s becomes a write-only cache populated by ESO.
    example: |
      # External Secrets Operator v0.9+
      apiVersion: external-secrets.io/v1beta1
      kind: ExternalSecret
      metadata:
        name: db-credentials
        namespace: production
      spec:
        refreshInterval: 1h
        secretStoreRef:
          name: aws-secretsmanager
          kind: ClusterSecretStore
        target:
          name: db-credentials
          creationPolicy: Owner
        data:
        - secretKey: DB_PASSWORD
          remoteRef:
            key: production/db
            property: password

  - id: namespace-isolation
    title: Separate workloads into namespaces with resource quotas
    description: >
      Use namespaces to enforce blast-radius isolation and resource fairness.
      Apply ResourceQuota and LimitRange to every non-system namespace so a
      runaway workload cannot starve the cluster.
    example: |
      apiVersion: v1
      kind: ResourceQuota
      metadata:
        name: production-quota
        namespace: production
      spec:
        hard:
          requests.cpu: "10"
          requests.memory: "20Gi"
          limits.cpu: "20"
          limits.memory: "40Gi"
          pods: "50"
      ---
      apiVersion: v1
      kind: LimitRange
      metadata:
        name: default-limits
        namespace: production
      spec:
        limits:
        - default:
            cpu: "500m"
            memory: "512Mi"
          defaultRequest:
            cpu: "100m"
            memory: "128Mi"
          type: Container

anti_patterns:
  - id: latest-image-tag
    title: Using 'latest' image tag in production
    description: >
      The 'latest' tag is mutable -- the same tag can point to different image digests
      at different times. A node pull after an image push can run a different version
      than other nodes, causing split-brain deployments. Always pin to a specific
      digest or immutable semver tag. ImagePullPolicy: Always with 'latest' makes this
      worse by pulling on every pod restart.

  - id: no-resource-limits
    title: Deploying containers without resource limits
    description: >
      Without limits, a container with a memory leak or runaway loop consumes all
      node memory, triggering the OOM killer to kill other pods on the same node.
      The node may then become NotReady. CPU starvation causes latency spikes across
      all co-located workloads.

  - id: readiness-as-liveness
    title: Using the same endpoint for both liveness and readiness
    description: >
      If the liveness probe hits the same endpoint as readiness, a temporarily
      overloaded pod (should be removed from load balancer) triggers container
      restarts instead. CrashLoopBackOff follows, compounding the outage. Liveness
      must test only "is the process alive"; readiness tests "can I handle requests".

  - id: privileged-containers
    title: Running containers as privileged or as root
    description: >
      privileged: true gives the container full host kernel access -- equivalent to
      root on the node. Running as UID 0 allows container escapes via known CVEs.
      Always set runAsNonRoot: true, readOnlyRootFilesystem: true, and
      allowPrivilegeEscalation: false in the securityContext.

  - id: cluster-admin-for-workloads
    title: Binding cluster-admin to application service accounts
    description: >
      ClusterRoleBinding with cluster-admin to an application SA means a compromised
      pod has full control of the cluster -- can read all secrets, exec into any pod,
      delete any resource. Workloads never need cluster-admin. Scope bindings to
      namespaced Roles with minimal verbs.

  - id: missing-pod-disruption-budget
    title: Skipping PodDisruptionBudget on multi-replica workloads
    description: >
      During node upgrades or voluntary evictions (kubectl drain), Kubernetes will
      evict pods without any regard for availability if no PDB exists. Two-replica
      Deployments can briefly drop to zero, causing downtime during routine maintenance.

gotchas:
  - id: oomkill-vs-crashloopbackoff
    title: OOMKill and CrashLoopBackOff have different root causes
    description: >
      OOMKill (exit code 137) means the container exceeded its memory limit -- the
      Linux OOM killer terminated it. CrashLoopBackOff means the container is
      repeatedly exiting (any non-zero exit code) and k8s is applying exponential
      backoff (10s, 20s, 40s, up to 5 min). OOMKill often looks like CrashLoopBackOff
      in describe output because the restart count climbs. Check
      'kubectl describe pod' for 'OOMKilled' in Last State before tuning probes.
    fix: >
      Run: kubectl describe pod <name> | grep -A5 "Last State"
      If OOMKilled: increase memory limit or fix memory leak.
      If non-OOM CrashLoop: kubectl logs <pod> --previous to see last exit output.

  - id: probe-timing-startup-race
    title: Liveness probe fires before app is ready on first start
    description: >
      If initialDelaySeconds is too low for liveness, the probe fails during app
      startup, triggering a restart before the app ever serves traffic. This loops
      forever. The fix in k8s 1.20+ is to use a startupProbe with a high
      failureThreshold (e.g., 30 x 10s = 5 min budget) -- liveness does not start
      until the startup probe succeeds.
    fix: >
      Add startupProbe with failureThreshold * periodSeconds >= max startup time.
      Remove initialDelaySeconds from livenessProbe when startupProbe is present.

  - id: pending-pods-resource-pressure
    title: Pods stuck in Pending due to insufficient node resources
    description: >
      A pod in Pending with no node assignment means the scheduler could not find a
      node satisfying requests + affinity rules. This is NOT a pod bug -- the cluster
      is undersized or requests are too high. 'kubectl describe pod' shows
      FailedScheduling events with the reason (Insufficient cpu, Insufficient memory,
      node(s) didn't match Pod's node affinity).
    fix: >
      kubectl describe pod <name> | grep -A10 Events
      Options: scale node pool, reduce requests, relax affinity, add node labels.

  - id: imagepullbackoff-causes
    title: ImagePullBackOff has four distinct root causes
    description: >
      ImagePullBackOff means the kubelet cannot pull the image. Causes: (1) image
      does not exist at that tag/digest, (2) registry requires authentication and
      imagePullSecrets is missing, (3) network policy blocks egress to the registry,
      (4) registry rate limiting (Docker Hub 100 pulls/6h for anonymous). Each needs
      a different fix. Check Events in describe pod for the exact error message.
    fix: >
      kubectl describe pod <name> | grep -A5 "Failed to pull"
      For auth: create docker-registry secret and reference in imagePullSecrets.
      For rate limits: use a registry mirror or authenticated pulls.

  - id: rbac-deny-by-default
    title: RBAC is deny-by-default -- missing rules silently block
    description: >
      If a ServiceAccount attempts an API call not covered by any Role/ClusterRole
      binding, the API server returns 403 Forbidden with no log by default. The
      workload just fails with a cryptic error. Enable audit logging or use
      'kubectl auth can-i <verb> <resource> --as=system:serviceaccount:<ns>:<sa>'
      to test before deploying.
    fix: >
      kubectl auth can-i get pods --as=system:serviceaccount:production:api-server -n production
      Add missing rules incrementally; never grant wildcard verbs to fix quickly.

  - id: service-account-token-auto-mount
    title: Default ServiceAccount token is mounted in every pod
    description: >
      Unless automountServiceAccountToken: false is set on the ServiceAccount or pod
      spec, every pod gets a projected token for the 'default' ServiceAccount at
      /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token. In k8s 1.24+ these are
      time-limited tokens, but they still allow unauthenticated pods to query the
      API server. Compromised pods can enumerate cluster resources.
    fix: >
      Set automountServiceAccountToken: false on the ServiceAccount definition.
      Override to true only on pods that genuinely need API access.

  - id: hpa-missing-requests
    title: HPA does not work without resource requests
    description: >
      HPA calculates utilization as (current usage / request). If requests are not
      set, HPA cannot compute a utilization percentage and the HPA object shows
      'unknown' for current metrics. Scale events never fire. This is a common
      "HPA isn't scaling" confusion.
    fix: >
      kubectl describe hpa <name> -- look for "unknown" in TARGETS column.
      Fix: add resource requests to all containers in the Deployment.


