### terraform

# Terraform Infrastructure Patterns
# Source: synthesized from production repositories and best practices
version: 1

patterns:
  - id: remote-state-with-locking
    title: Remote state with DynamoDB locking (AWS) or GCS locking (GCP)
    description: >
      Never use local state in a team environment. Remote state enables collaboration
      and state locking prevents concurrent applies from corrupting the state file.
      S3 + DynamoDB is the canonical AWS backend. State must be versioned so
      corrupted state can be rolled back.
    example: |
      # backend.tf
      terraform {
        backend "s3" {
          bucket         = "my-terraform-state-prod"
          key            = "services/api/terraform.tfstate"
          region         = "us-east-1"
          encrypt        = true
          dynamodb_table = "terraform-state-lock"
        }
        required_version = ">= 1.5.0"
        required_providers {
          aws = {
            source  = "hashicorp/aws"
            version = "~> 5.0"
          }
        }
      }

  - id: workspace-strategy
    title: Workspaces for environment isolation, not feature branches
    description: >
      Terraform workspaces isolate state per environment (dev/staging/prod) within
      the same configuration. Use workspaces when infra is structurally identical
      across environments and only variable values differ. For fundamentally different
      infra (e.g., prod has multi-AZ, dev does not), use separate root modules instead.
    example: |
      # Create and switch workspace
      terraform workspace new staging
      terraform workspace select staging

      # Reference workspace in config
      locals {
        env = terraform.workspace
        instance_type = {
          dev     = "t3.micro"
          staging = "t3.medium"
          prod    = "m5.large"
        }[local.env]
      }

  - id: module-versioning
    title: Pin module versions with semantic version constraints
    description: >
      Unpinned modules (source = "terraform-aws-modules/vpc/aws") pull the latest
      version on every init, causing non-deterministic plans. Pin with a version
      constraint. Use pessimistic constraint (~>) to allow patch updates but not
      breaking major/minor bumps.
    example: |
      module "vpc" {
        source  = "terraform-aws-modules/vpc/aws"
        version = "~> 5.1"

        name = "production-vpc"
        cidr = "10.0.0.0/16"
        azs  = ["us-east-1a", "us-east-1b", "us-east-1c"]
        private_subnets = ["10.0.1.0/24", "10.0.2.0/24", "10.0.3.0/24"]
        public_subnets  = ["10.0.101.0/24", "10.0.102.0/24", "10.0.103.0/24"]
        enable_nat_gateway = true
      }

  - id: for-each-over-count
    title: Prefer for_each over count for resource collections
    description: >
      count creates resources indexed by integer (aws_instance.server[0]).
      Removing an item from the middle shifts all subsequent indices, causing
      Terraform to destroy and recreate resources that did not change. for_each
      keys resources by a stable string key so removals are surgical.
    example: |
      # Good -- removing "staging" only destroys that one bucket
      variable "environments" {
        default = ["dev", "staging", "prod"]
      }

      resource "aws_s3_bucket" "env_buckets" {
        for_each = toset(var.environments)
        bucket   = "myapp-${each.key}-artifacts"
      }

      # Bad -- removing "staging" shifts prod from index 2 to 1, triggering destroy/recreate
      # resource "aws_s3_bucket" "env_buckets" {
      #   count  = length(var.environments)
      #   bucket = "myapp-${var.environments[count.index]}-artifacts"
      # }

  - id: data-sources-for-existing-resources
    title: Use data sources to reference resources not owned by this module
    description: >
      Never hardcode ARNs or IDs for resources owned by another Terraform root module
      or by hand. Use data sources so the reference stays live and plan output shows
      the actual resolved value. Remote state outputs are the preferred alternative
      for cross-module references.
    example: |
      # Reference a VPC created in another root module
      data "terraform_remote_state" "networking" {
        backend = "s3"
        config = {
          bucket = "my-terraform-state-prod"
          key    = "networking/terraform.tfstate"
          region = "us-east-1"
        }
      }

      resource "aws_security_group" "app" {
        vpc_id = data.terraform_remote_state.networking.outputs.vpc_id
        # ...
      }

  - id: import-blocks-tf-1-5
    title: Use import blocks (TF 1.5+) for bringing existing resources under management
    description: >
      The 'terraform import' CLI command requires running import before plan/apply and
      does not generate config. TF 1.5+ import blocks let you declare the import
      alongside config so it runs as part of apply. TF 1.6+ can also auto-generate
      config with 'terraform plan -generate-config-out=generated.tf'.
    example: |
      # import.tf (TF 1.5+)
      import {
        to = aws_s3_bucket.legacy_bucket
        id = "my-existing-bucket-name"
      }

      resource "aws_s3_bucket" "legacy_bucket" {
        bucket = "my-existing-bucket-name"
        # fill in attributes matching current state
      }

      # Then run: terraform plan
      # Terraform shows import + diff without separate import command

  - id: provider-version-pinning
    title: Pin provider versions in required_providers
    description: >
      Provider minor/patch releases frequently introduce behavioral changes or new
      required attributes. Pin with ~> to allow patch updates but block breaking
      minor bumps. Run 'terraform init -upgrade' deliberately when ready to upgrade,
      and always review the provider changelog.
    example: |
      terraform {
        required_providers {
          aws = {
            source  = "hashicorp/aws"
            version = "~> 5.31"
          }
          kubernetes = {
            source  = "hashicorp/kubernetes"
            version = "~> 2.25"
          }
          random = {
            source  = "hashicorp/random"
            version = "~> 3.6"
          }
        }
      }

  - id: depends-on-sparingly
    title: Use depends_on only for hidden dependencies
    description: >
      Terraform infers dependencies from resource attribute references. depends_on
      creates an opaque dependency that Terraform cannot optimize away -- it forces
      sequential apply even when parallel would be safe. Use depends_on only when
      a resource has a side effect not captured in its attributes (e.g., an IAM
      policy must exist before an assume-role can succeed, but the ARN is not
      referenced in the resource block).
    example: |
      # Only needed when IAM propagation must complete before Lambda invoke
      resource "aws_lambda_function" "processor" {
        # ...
        depends_on = [aws_iam_role_policy_attachment.lambda_policy]
      }

anti_patterns:
  - id: local-state-in-team
    title: Committing terraform.tfstate to version control
    description: >
      State files contain plaintext sensitive values (passwords, keys, certificates).
      Concurrent applies on local state corrupt the file -- the last writer wins
      and silently drops the other's changes. Remote state with locking is mandatory
      for any team usage.

  - id: hardcoded-credentials-in-provider
    title: Hardcoding cloud credentials in provider blocks
    description: >
      access_key and secret_key in the AWS provider block (or equivalent) end up in
      the Terraform config, .terraform directory, and potentially plan files. Use
      environment variables (AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID), instance profiles, OIDC federation,
      or workload identity instead. Provider blocks must have zero credential fields.

  - id: count-for-mutable-sets
    title: Using count for sets of resources that change over time
    description: >
      When items are added or removed from the middle of a count-indexed list, all
      higher-indexed resources get a new index. Terraform interprets this as
      destroy-old-index + create-new-index, not a move. A list reorder destroys and
      recreates production databases. Use for_each with a stable string key.

  - id: no-version-constraints
    title: Omitting Terraform and provider version constraints
    description: >
      Without version constraints, 'terraform init' installs whatever is latest.
      Provider 5.x may not be compatible with configs written for 4.x. A new team
      member running init after a major provider release gets a different provider
      than CI, causing "inconsistent dependency lock file" errors and potential
      plan drift.

  - id: single-root-module-all-environments
    title: Managing all environments from one root module with variables
    description: >
      Sharing one state file across dev/staging/prod means a botched plan for dev
      can destroy prod resources. Separate root modules (or workspaces) per
      environment provide blast-radius isolation. A mistake in dev state never
      touches prod state.

  - id: ignore-plan-output
    title: Running terraform apply without reviewing the plan
    description: >
      'terraform apply' without '-plan=<planfile>' re-runs planning. If infra changed
      between plan and apply, you apply a different plan than reviewed. Always save
      the plan: 'terraform plan -out=tfplan' then 'terraform apply tfplan'. In CI,
      treat the plan file as an artifact and fail the pipeline if apply does not
      use it.

gotchas:
  - id: state-corruption-on-interrupt
    title: Interrupted apply can leave state in partial/corrupt state
    description: >
      If 'terraform apply' is killed mid-run (Ctrl+C, CI timeout, network drop),
      some resources may be created but not recorded in state, or state may reference
      resources that failed to create. The next plan will show unexpected changes.
      DynamoDB locking releases on clean exit but NOT on hard kill -- a stale lock
      may block the next apply.
    fix: >
      Check for stale lock: terraform force-unlock <LOCK_ID> (get ID from error msg).
      Reconcile state: terraform plan to see drift, then terraform import or
      terraform state rm to repair. Never edit .tfstate directly.

  - id: terraform-destroy-ordering
    title: terraform destroy reverses dependency order but some resources resist
    description: >
      Destroy proceeds in reverse dependency order, but resources with deletion
      protection (RDS, S3 with objects, ECR with images) will fail mid-destroy,
      leaving the state partially destroyed. Non-empty S3 buckets block bucket
      deletion. The apply half-succeeds, leaving orphaned resources.
    fix: >
      For S3: set force_destroy = true in resource config before running destroy.
      For RDS: set deletion_protection = false and apply before destroy.
      Review destroy plan carefully before confirming.

  - id: tainted-resources
    title: Tainted resources are destroyed and recreated on next apply
    description: >
      A resource is marked tainted when apply partially fails during creation.
      The next plan shows it as destroy+create, not update. Tainted production
      databases will be destroyed. Review tainted resources: 'terraform state list'
      and 'terraform show' before any apply following a failed run.
    fix: >
      terraform state list | grep tainted  (look for -tainted suffix)
      terraform untaint <resource_address>  (TF 1.x uses 'terraform taint' to add,
      remove with 'terraform untaint')

  - id: sensitive-values-in-state
    title: Sensitive outputs and resource attributes are stored in plaintext state
    description: >
      Even when a variable or output is marked sensitive = true, its value is stored
      in plaintext in the state file. S3 backend encryption (encrypt = true) encrypts
      at rest, but the state is decrypted by anyone with s3:GetObject on the bucket.
      Database passwords, API keys, and certificates in state must be protected by
      strict IAM policies on the state bucket.
    fix: >
      Minimize secrets in state: use data sources to read secrets at apply time from
      Secrets Manager rather than storing them as resource attributes. Restrict
      state bucket access to CI role and operators only.

  - id: refresh-vs-plan-divergence
    title: terraform plan output depends on whether refresh is included
    description: >
      By default, 'terraform plan' runs a refresh (queries cloud APIs for current
      state) before computing the diff. 'terraform plan -refresh=false' skips refresh
      and diffs against cached state only. In CI, -refresh=false is faster but misses
      out-of-band changes. The plan file from -refresh=false may be stale by apply
      time.
    fix: >
      Always run with refresh enabled in CI unless you explicitly want speed over
      accuracy. Use terraform apply -refresh-only periodically to sync state without
      making changes.

  - id: provider-upgrade-breaking-changes
    title: Provider major version upgrades frequently require config rewrites
    description: >
      The AWS provider v4 -> v5 removed the aws_s3_bucket all-in-one resource in
      favor of separate sub-resources (aws_s3_bucket_versioning, etc.). Upgrading
      the provider version constraint without reading the CHANGELOG causes 'An
      argument named X is not expected here' errors and requires config migration
      before plan will succeed.
    fix: >
      Before bumping provider version in required_providers: read provider CHANGELOG
      for the version range being crossed. Run: terraform init -upgrade, then
      terraform plan to surface breaking changes. Address each one before applying.


### tmdl-authoring

# TMDL Authoring Reference

Companion to `pbip-format.md`. Covers patterns and gotchas for writing correct TMDL content — the semantic model layer of a .pbip project.

Referenced by: client-work

---

## The `_measures` Table Pattern

Centralize all measures in a single table with no data rows. This is a best practice for maintainability.

In TMDL, create a table with no partitions and no columns — measures only:

```
table _Measures
	lineageTag: <leave existing, omit when creating new>

	measure 'Total Sales' = SUM(FactSales[SalesAmount])
		formatString: "$#,0.00;($#,0.00);$#,0.00"
		displayFolder: Revenue

	measure 'Sales QoQ %' = DIVIDE([Total Sales] - [Sales PQ], [Sales PQ])
		formatString: "0.0%"
		displayFolder: Revenue
```

Benefits:
- All business logic in one place — easy to find, audit, and document
- No calculated column clutter mixing with measures in the same table
- Cleanly separates storage (fact/dim tables) from calculation (measures table)

---

## Relationship Direction — Default to Single

Always default to single-direction cross-filtering. Only allow bi-directional when the model explicitly requires it, and document why.

**Why single-direction:**
- Bi-directional relationships can create ambiguous filter paths when multiple relationship chains exist
- They hide context transitions that are obvious in single-direction models
- They can cause performance issues on large models by expanding filter propagation unexpectedly

**When bi-directional is acceptable:**
- Many-to-many relationships that require it by design
- Bridge tables (role-playing dimensions)
- Always document with a `/// Reason: bi-directional required because...` annotation

**In TMDL:**
```
relationship FactSales-DimProduct
	fromTable: FactSales
	fromColumn: ProductKey
	toTable: DimProduct
	toColumn: ProductKey
	// crossFilteringBehavior: bothDirections  ← only add if required
```

---

## Calculation Groups

Calculation groups in TMDL use a `calculationGroup` block inside a table:

```
table 'Time Intelligence'
	calculationGroup
		precedence: 10

		calculationItem YTD = CALCULATE(SELECTEDMEASURE(), DATESYTD(DimDate[Date]))
			/// Year-to-date from Jan 1 to the last visible date

		calculationItem QTD = CALCULATE(SELECTEDMEASURE(), DATESQTD(DimDate[Date]))
			/// Quarter-to-date

		calculationItem MTD = CALCULATE(SELECTEDMEASURE(), DATESMTD(DimDate[Date]))
			/// Month-to-date

		calculationItem PY = CALCULATE(SELECTEDMEASURE(), SAMEPERIODLASTYEAR(DimDate[Date]))
			/// Prior year same period
```

**Gotcha:** Field parameters referencing a calculation group measure in Power BI resolve to ALL contained calculation items — not just the active one. If a field parameter appears to return multiple values, this is why.

---

## Field Parameter Gotcha

When a field parameter references a measure, it resolves to ALL measures contained in the parameter's value list — not just the currently selected one. This is by design but surprises most developers.

**Symptom:** A card visual showing a field parameter measure displays data that looks like a total of multiple measures.

**Fix:** The field parameter is working correctly — the visual's filter context is not set to a single item. Ensure the slicer driving the field parameter has single-select enabled and the visual is filtered accordingly.

---

## Three-Level Rename Chain

Every column in Power BI has three names that must all be tracked when renaming:

```
source_name (in the source database)
  → pq_name (the name after Power Query transformations)
    → pbi_name (the name visible in the model and DAX)
```

**When you rename a column in TMDL**, you are renaming `pbi_name`. You must also check:
1. `sourceColumn` property in the column definition (links to `pq_name`)
2. Any `Table.RenameColumns` steps in the M expression that produce `pq_name`
3. All DAX measures that reference `Table[ColumnName]` using `pbi_name`

**When you rename a Power Query step output**, you are changing `pq_name`. You must check:
1. The `sourceColumn` in TMDL that references this name
2. The `name` property of the column in TMDL

Never rename without tracing the full chain.

---

## Session Workflow

Safe TMDL editing workflow:
1. **Inspect first** — read the current TMDL before making any change
2. **Small changes** — edit one measure or one table at a time
3. **Validate immediately** — open the .pbip in Power BI Desktop after every edit; a parse error shows as a red warning in the field list
4. **Never batch** — don't queue 10 edits and validate once at the end; one bad tab character can corrupt the whole table block
5. **Python for file ops** — use Python with UTF-8 encoding when reading/writing TMDL; Windows shell tools break on accented characters


